---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Least Squares Estimation">
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container learn-container">

      <nav class="breadcrumb">
        <a href="/learn">Learn</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <a href="/learn/mathematics">Mathematics</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <span>Least Squares Estimation</span>
      </nav>

      <div class="article-header">
        <span class="badge">Mathematics · Article 1 of 5</span>
        <h1>Least Squares Estimation</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          Every time your receiver computes a position from satellite pseudoranges, it solves a
          least squares problem. With more satellites than unknowns, there is no exact solution —
          least squares finds the position that best fits all the measurements simultaneously,
          minimising the total squared error. This is the mathematical engine inside every
          GNSS receiver.
        </p>
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span>14 min read</span>
          <span>·</span>
          <span>Last updated March 2026</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="toc">
        <div class="toc-title">Contents</div>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#problem">The overdetermined system</a></li>
          <li><a href="#linear-ls">Linear least squares</a></li>
          <li><a href="#normal-equations">The normal equations</a></li>
          <li><a href="#gnss-application">Application to GNSS positioning</a></li>
          <li><a href="#weighted-ls">Weighted least squares</a></li>
          <li><a href="#residuals">Residuals and quality control</a></li>
          <li><a href="#covariance">Covariance of the estimate</a></li>
          <li><a href="#nonlinear">Nonlinear least squares — iterative solution</a></li>
          <li><a href="#summary">Summary</a></li>
          <li><a href="#references">References</a></li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 1 -->
      <h2 id="problem">The overdetermined system</h2>
      <p>
        Suppose you measure the pseudorange to 8 satellites but only need 4 to solve for position.
        You have 8 equations and 4 unknowns — an <strong>overdetermined system</strong>. No single
        position (x, y, z, δt) satisfies all 8 equations exactly because each measurement contains
        noise. The question becomes: which position best fits all measurements simultaneously?
      </p>
      <p>
        In matrix form, the observation system is:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">y = Ax + ε</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          <strong>y</strong> (n×1) = vector of observations (e.g. pseudoranges)<br/>
          <strong>A</strong> (n×m) = design matrix (partial derivatives, n &gt; m)<br/>
          <strong>x</strong> (m×1) = vector of unknowns (position, clock offset)<br/>
          <strong>ε</strong> (n×1) = vector of observation errors (noise)<br/>
          n = number of observations, m = number of unknowns. For overdetermined: n &gt; m.
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        Least squares finds the estimate <strong>x̂</strong> that minimises the sum of squared
        residuals — the squared differences between observed and modelled values:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">minimise J = εᵀε = (y − Ax̂)ᵀ(y − Ax̂)</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          The cost function J is a quadratic bowl in x̂-space — it has a unique global minimum.
          Setting ∂J/∂x̂ = 0 gives the normal equations.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Visual intuition -->
      <div class="intuition-box">
        <div class="ib-title">Geometric intuition</div>
        <div class="ib-body">
          Think of each observation as a line in solution space. With n equations and m unknowns
          (n &gt; m), the lines don't all pass through a single point — they form a cluster.
          Least squares finds the point that minimises the sum of squared perpendicular distances
          to all observation lines simultaneously. The result sits at the "centre of gravity"
          of the cluster of measurement constraints.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 2 -->
      <h2 id="linear-ls">Linear least squares</h2>
      <p>
        When the observations depend linearly on the unknowns (A is constant), the least squares
        solution is found analytically in one step. Taking the derivative of J with respect to x̂
        and setting it to zero:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">∂J/∂x̂ = −2Aᵀ(y − Ax̂) = 0</div>
        <div class="formula">⟹  Aᵀy = AᵀAx̂</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          This gives the <strong>normal equations</strong>: AᵀAx̂ = Aᵀy.
          The matrix AᵀA is square (m×m) and — if A has full column rank — invertible.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 3 -->
      <h2 id="normal-equations">The normal equations</h2>
      <p>
        Solving the normal equations gives the least squares estimate:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">x̂ = (AᵀA)⁻¹ Aᵀy</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          The matrix (AᵀA)⁻¹Aᵀ is called the <strong>pseudo-inverse</strong> of A (also written A⁺).
          It generalises the matrix inverse to non-square systems.
          When n = m (exactly determined), A is square and x̂ = A⁻¹y exactly.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="worked-example">
        <div class="we-title">Worked example — 2D position from three ranges</div>
        <div class="we-body">
          <p>
            Three known points (beacons) at positions (0,0), (10,0), (5,10) m.
            Measured ranges: r₁ = 7.1 m, r₂ = 7.2 m, r₃ = 5.2 m.
            Find the 2D position (x, y).
          </p>
          <p>
            Linearise around initial estimate (x₀, y₀) = (5, 5). The design matrix A has rows:
          </p>
          <div class="we-matrix">
            <code>A = [-(x₀-bx₁)/r₁  -(y₀-by₁)/r₁]   row 1: beacon 1</code>
            <code>    [-(x₀-bx₂)/r₂  -(y₀-by₂)/r₂]   row 2: beacon 2</code>
            <code>    [-(x₀-bx₃)/r₃  -(y₀-by₃)/r₃]   row 3: beacon 3</code>
          </div>
          <p>
            Compute AᵀA (2×2), Aᵀy (2×1), solve x̂ = (AᵀA)⁻¹Aᵀy.
            Iterate 2–3 times until Δx̂ &lt; 1 mm.
            This is exactly what a GNSS receiver does — in 4D (x, y, z, δt) with 4–40 satellites.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 4 -->
      <h2 id="gnss-application">Application to GNSS positioning</h2>
      <p>
        In GNSS, the observations are pseudoranges ρᵢ and the unknowns are receiver position
        (x, y, z) and clock offset δt. The pseudorange model for satellite i at position
        (xˢ, yˢ, zˢ) is:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">ρᵢ = √[(x−xˢᵢ)² + (y−yˢᵢ)² + (z−zˢᵢ)²] + c·δt + εᵢ</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          This is nonlinear — the position appears inside a square root. It must be linearised
          around an approximate position (x₀, y₀, z₀, δt₀) before applying least squares.
          Define: Δx = x−x₀, Δy = y−y₀, Δz = z−z₀, Δδt = δt−δt₀.
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The linearised observation equation for satellite i becomes:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">Δρᵢ = −(xˢᵢ−x₀)/r₀ᵢ · Δx − (yˢᵢ−y₀)/r₀ᵢ · Δy − (zˢᵢ−z₀)/r₀ᵢ · Δz + c·Δδt + εᵢ</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          where r₀ᵢ = √[(x₀−xˢᵢ)² + (y₀−yˢᵢ)² + (z₀−zˢᵢ)²] is the geometric range
          from approximate position to satellite i, and Δρᵢ = ρᵢ − r₀ᵢ − c·δt₀ is the
          observed minus computed pseudorange residual.
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        For n satellites, this gives the design matrix A (n × 4):
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">A = ⎡−(xˢ₁−x₀)/r₀₁  −(yˢ₁−y₀)/r₀₁  −(zˢ₁−z₀)/r₀₁  1⎤</div>
        <div class="formula">    ⎢−(xˢ₂−x₀)/r₀₂  −(yˢ₂−y₀)/r₀₂  −(zˢ₂−z₀)/r₀₂  1⎥</div>
        <div class="formula">    ⎢       ⋮                ⋮                ⋮          ⋮⎥</div>
        <div class="formula">    ⎣−(xˢₙ−x₀)/r₀ₙ  −(yˢₙ−y₀)/r₀ₙ  −(zˢₙ−z₀)/r₀ₙ  1⎦</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          Each row contains the unit vector from the approximate receiver position toward
          satellite i (with sign negated), plus a 1 for the clock column.
          Note: (AᵀA)⁻¹ = Q is exactly the DOP covariance matrix. HDOP, VDOP and PDOP
          are extracted from the diagonal of Q — connecting DOP directly to least squares.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 5 -->
      <h2 id="weighted-ls">Weighted least squares</h2>
      <p>
        Standard least squares treats all observations equally. In GNSS, this is unrealistic —
        a satellite at 5° elevation has far more noise (ionosphere, troposphere, multipath) than
        one at 70°. <strong>Weighted least squares (WLS)</strong> assigns each observation a
        weight inversely proportional to its expected variance.
      </p>

      <p>
        The weight matrix W (n×n, diagonal) modifies the cost function:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">minimise J = εᵀWε = (y − Ax̂)ᵀ W (y − Ax̂)</div>
        <div class="formula">⟹  x̂ = (AᵀWA)⁻¹ AᵀWy</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          W = diag(w₁, w₂, ..., wₙ) where wᵢ = σ₀²/σᵢ² = 1/σᵢ² (if σ₀ = 1).
          Higher weight = more trusted observation. Lower elevation → higher σᵢ → lower weight.
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Common GNSS weighting models</h3>
      <div class="weight-models">
        <div class="wm-card">
          <div class="wm-name">Elevation-based</div>
          <div class="wm-formula">wᵢ = sin²(elᵢ)</div>
          <div class="wm-desc">Most common. Low elevation satellites get low weight. Simple and effective for most scenarios.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="wm-card">
          <div class="wm-name">SNR-based</div>
          <div class="wm-formula">wᵢ ∝ 10^(SNRᵢ/10)</div>
          <div class="wm-desc">Uses actual signal strength. Better in obstructed environments where elevation is a poor proxy for signal quality.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="wm-card">
          <div class="wm-name">Variance model</div>
          <div class="wm-formula">σᵢ² = a² + b²/sin²(elᵢ)</div>
          <div class="wm-desc">Combines a noise floor (a) with elevation-dependent term (b). Used in many professional receiver engines.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 6 -->
      <h2 id="residuals">Residuals and quality control</h2>
      <p>
        After computing x̂, the <strong>residuals</strong> (post-fit residuals or v-vector) reveal
        how well the model fits the data:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">v = y − Ax̂ = y − A(AᵀA)⁻¹Aᵀy = (I − A(AᵀA)⁻¹Aᵀ)y</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          v contains the part of y that cannot be explained by the model.
          Under the assumption that errors are Gaussian with zero mean, the residuals should
          also be small, zero-mean and uncorrelated. Large residuals indicate outliers (blunders),
          unmodelled errors (multipath) or wrong satellite identification.
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Data snooping — outlier detection</h3>
      <p>
        A single large measurement error (blunder) corrupts the entire least squares solution.
        <strong>Data snooping</strong> (Baarda, 1968) tests each residual against a threshold
        to detect and remove outliers:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">wᵢ = vᵢ / σ_vᵢ</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          wᵢ = normalised residual for observation i.
          σ_vᵢ = √(σ₀² · Qᵥᵥ[i,i]) = standard deviation of residual i from the cofactor matrix.
          If |wᵢ| &gt; 3.29 (α = 0.001 significance level), observation i is flagged as an outlier
          and removed. The system is re-solved without it. This is the basis of RAIM
          (Receiver Autonomous Integrity Monitoring).
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 7 -->
      <h2 id="covariance">Covariance of the estimate</h2>
      <p>
        The least squares estimate x̂ is a random variable — it has uncertainty because the
        observations y contain noise. The <strong>covariance matrix</strong> of x̂ quantifies
        this uncertainty:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">Q_x̂ = σ₀² (AᵀA)⁻¹</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          σ₀² = a priori variance of unit weight (assumed equal to 1 if observations have
          been properly scaled by their standard deviations before forming W).
          The diagonal elements of Q_x̂ are the variances of each estimated parameter:
          σ²_x, σ²_y, σ²_z, σ²_δt.
          HDOP = √(Q_x̂[1,1] + Q_x̂[2,2]) — DOP values come directly from this matrix.
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The <strong>a posteriori variance factor</strong> σ̂₀² estimates σ₀² from the data:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">σ̂₀² = vᵀv / (n − m) = vᵀWv / (n − m)</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          n − m = degrees of freedom (number of observations minus number of unknowns).
          If σ̂₀² ≈ 1, the assumed noise model is consistent with the data.
          If σ̂₀² &gt;&gt; 1, the observations are noisier than assumed — check for unmodelled errors.
          If σ̂₀² &lt;&lt; 1, the assumed sigmas may be too pessimistic.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 8 -->
      <h2 id="nonlinear">Nonlinear least squares — iterative solution</h2>
      <p>
        The GNSS pseudorange equation is nonlinear. The linearisation above is only valid near
        the expansion point (x₀, y₀, z₀). The full iterative procedure is:
      </p>

      <ol class="steps">
        <li>
          <strong>Initialise:</strong> Set (x₀, y₀, z₀, δt₀) — last known position, or Earth's
          centre for cold start. Compute satellite positions from ephemeris.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Compute predicted ranges:</strong> r₀ᵢ = ‖position₀ − satelliteᵢ‖ for each
          satellite. Compute observed-minus-predicted: Δρᵢ = ρᵢ − r₀ᵢ − c·δt₀.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Build design matrix A:</strong> Direction cosines from (x₀, y₀, z₀) to each
          satellite, plus clock column of ones.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Solve:</strong> Δx̂ = (AᵀWA)⁻¹ AᵀW Δρ. Apply corrections:
          x₀ ← x₀ + Δx̂.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Check convergence:</strong> If ‖Δx̂‖ &lt; threshold (e.g. 1 mm), stop.
          Otherwise, go to step 2 with updated position.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <p>
        Convergence typically takes 3–5 iterations from a reasonable starting point.
        From a cold start (x₀ = Earth's centre), 10–15 iterations may be needed.
        The algorithm is guaranteed to converge because the GNSS pseudorange function
        is well-conditioned near the true solution.
      </p>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">🔗</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Connection to DOP:</strong> The matrix Q = (AᵀA)⁻¹ from the unweighted
          solution is exactly the DOP covariance matrix introduced in the
          <a href="/learn/fundamentals/dilution-of-precision">DOP article</a>.
          PDOP = σ₀ √(Q[1,1] + Q[2,2] + Q[3,3]), HDOP = σ₀ √(Q[1,1] + Q[2,2]),
          VDOP = σ₀ √(Q[3,3]). Everything connects through least squares.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 9 - SUMMARY -->
      <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
      <div class="summary-grid">
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">📐</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Minimise squared residuals</div>
          <div class="summary-body">x̂ = (AᵀA)⁻¹Aᵀy. The normal equations have a unique solution when A has full column rank (satellites not all in one plane).</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">⚖️</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Weight by reliability</div>
          <div class="summary-body">x̂ = (AᵀWA)⁻¹AᵀWy. Low-elevation and low-SNR satellites get lower weight. Weighted LS is standard in all quality receivers.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🔍</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Residuals reveal problems</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Post-fit residuals v = y − Ax̂. Large normalised residuals (|w| &gt; 3.29) indicate outliers. Data snooping removes blunders one at a time.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🔄</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Iterate for nonlinear problems</div>
          <div class="summary-body">GNSS is nonlinear — linearise around current estimate, solve, update. Repeat 3–5 times. Q = (AᵀA)⁻¹ is the DOP matrix — least squares and DOP are one and the same.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="nav-footer">
        <a href="/learn/mathematics" class="nav-prev">← Mathematics</a>
        <a href="/learn/mathematics/kalman-filter" class="nav-next">Kalman Filter →</a>
      </div>

      <div class="references" id="references">
        <h3>References and further reading</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Teunissen, P. J. G. (2000). <em>Adjustment Theory — An Introduction</em>. Delft University Press.</li>
          <li>Koch, K. R. (1999). <em>Parameter Estimation and Hypothesis Testing in Linear Models</em>, 2nd ed. Springer.</li>
          <li>Kaplan, E. D. & Hegarty, C. J. (2017). <em>Understanding GPS/GNSS: Principles and Applications</em>, 3rd ed. Artech House. Chapter 7.</li>
          <li>Baarda, W. (1968). A testing procedure for use in geodetic networks. <em>Publications on Geodesy</em>, New Series 2(5). Netherlands Geodetic Commission.</li>
          <li>Misra, P. & Enge, P. (2011). <em>Global Positioning System: Signals, Measurements and Performance</em>, 2nd ed. Chapter 5.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .learn-container { max-width: 820px; }
  .breadcrumb { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; font-size: 13px; color: var(--text3); margin-bottom: 28px; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .breadcrumb a { color: var(--text2); transition: color 0.2s; }
  .breadcrumb a:hover { color: var(--accent); }
  .article-header { margin-bottom: 36px; }
  h1 { font-size: clamp(24px, 4vw, 38px); font-weight: 700; margin: 10px 0 16px; line-height: 1.2; }
  h2 { font-size: 22px; font-weight: 700; margin: 40px 0 16px; padding-top: 8px; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); }
  h3 { font-size: 17px; font-weight: 600; margin: 28px 0 12px; }
  .lead { font-size: 17px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 12px; max-width: 720px; }
  .article-meta { font-size: 12px; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); display: flex; gap: 8px; }
  p { font-size: 15px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 16px; }
  ul { font-size: 15px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; padding-left: 24px; margin-bottom: 16px; }
  li { margin-bottom: 6px; }
  strong { color: var(--text); font-weight: 600; }
  a { color: var(--accent2); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px; }

  .toc { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 20px 24px; margin-bottom: 40px; }
  .toc-title { font-size: 11px; font-weight: 600; letter-spacing: 0.1em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); margin-bottom: 10px; }
  .toc ol { margin: 0; padding-left: 18px; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 6px; }
  .toc li { font-size: 14px; }
  .toc a { color: var(--text2); text-decoration: none; }
  .toc a:hover { color: var(--accent); }

  .callout { display: flex; gap: 14px; padding: 16px 20px; border-radius: 10px; margin: 24px 0; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.7; }
  .callout-icon { font-size: 18px; flex-shrink: 0; }
  .callout-info { background: rgba(0,153,255,0.06); border: 1px solid rgba(0,153,255,0.18); color: var(--text2); }
  .callout strong { color: var(--text); }

  .formula-block { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-left: 3px solid var(--accent); border-radius: 8px; padding: 18px 20px; margin: 20px 0; overflow-x: auto; }
  .formula { font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 14px; color: var(--text); margin-bottom: 4px; line-height: 1.8; white-space: pre; }
  .formula-desc { font-size: 13px; color: var(--text3); line-height: 1.7; margin-top: 10px; }

  /* Intuition box */
  .intuition-box { background: rgba(0,212,170,0.04); border: 1px solid rgba(0,212,170,0.2); border-radius: 10px; padding: 18px 20px; margin: 20px 0; }
  .ib-title { font-size: 13px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--accent); margin-bottom: 8px; }
  .ib-body { font-size: 14px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.7; }

  /* Worked example */
  .worked-example { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 18px 20px; margin: 20px 0; }
  .we-title { font-size: 13px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text); margin-bottom: 12px; font-family: var(--mono); }
  .we-body p { font-size: 14px; color: var(--text2); margin-bottom: 10px; }
  .we-matrix { background: var(--bg3); border-radius: 6px; padding: 10px 14px; margin: 10px 0; }
  .we-matrix code { display: block; font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 12px; color: var(--accent2); line-height: 1.8; }

  /* Weight models */
  .weight-models { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr); gap: 12px; margin: 16px 0; }
  .wm-card { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 16px; }
  .wm-name { font-size: 13px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text); margin-bottom: 6px; }
  .wm-formula { font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 12px; color: var(--accent); background: var(--bg3); padding: 4px 8px; border-radius: 4px; margin-bottom: 8px; display: inline-block; }
  .wm-desc { font-size: 12px; color: var(--text3); line-height: 1.6; }

  /* Steps */
  .steps { counter-reset: step; list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 16px 0; }
  .steps li { counter-increment: step; padding: 12px 12px 12px 48px; position: relative; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); font-size: 14px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.7; }
  .steps li:last-child { border-bottom: none; }
